The conclave focused on key issues: addressing priest sex-abuse scandals, priest shortages, declining church attendance, and improving relations with the Islamic world.
Cardinals debated between an older transitional pope or a younger communicator to succeed John Paul II.
They adhered to strict rules banning communication with the outside world.
The voting process involved special smoke signals.
The cardinals, representing 52 countries, took an oath of secrecy before entering the Sistine Chapel.
The selection process was shrouded in secrecy, with potential candidates from various continents under consideration.
The world awaited the announcement of the new pope with anticipation.
